AB  - Background: An angiogenic imbalance is among the theories for the pathogenesis of preeclampsia (PE) which is a health issue that is predicted to be cause of significant maternal and fetal mortality and morbidity. The PE clinical pattern is variable and its course is unpredictable and may end with a disastrous but a preventable result; henceearly diagnosis of PE and prediction of its morbiditiesare valuable and warrants a workthat enables a clinicianto interfere early before a significant prejudice results. Objective: To evaluate the role ofsoluble fms-like tyrosine kinase 1(sFlt), placental growth factor (PlGF) serum levels and their ratio in the diagnosis of PE. Patients and methods: This randomized case-control study hasinvolved eighty pregnant women, 40 of them werediagnosed to have PEand 40 apparently healthy pregnant womenas a control group. It was conducted at twoteaching hospitals in Baghdad city-Iraq. For all participants, serum levels of the twoangiogenic markers were measured and the ratio of their levels was calculated. Results: In PE women, mean serum level of PlGF was significantly lower than that in the control group (87.75 versus 284.2 ng/l) while mean level of sFlt-1 and mean value of s-Flt/PlGF ratio were significantly higher(5.45 versus 2.89 ng/l and 78.29 versus 12.31,respectively). A cut-ff value of 35 for sFlt-1/PlGF ratiohasachieved a sensitivity of 100%, a specificity of 100% and a diagnostic accuracy of 100%. Conclusion: The study angiogenic markers and particularly their ratio have a significant diagnostic performance in PEthat may warrant their clinical use. © 2020 Wolters Kluwer Medknow Publications. All rights reserved.
