AB  - International interventions require credible, verifiable information in order to pursue their work to build peace, foster stability and reduce armed violence. As the above discussion has demonstrated, however, unofficial information and data in settings of armed conflict are inherently ambiguous, enigmatic and positional, and often highly politicized. For many communities living in a context of war and intervention, rumour also has a sticky quality that 'can substitute for factual information and then preclude the need to search for actual fact'.119 For international interventions, therefore, there are enormous risks attached to ignoring the epistemological force of rumours. Such is the case for Mali, where 'any event is followed by an enormous dust storm of rumours'.120 The above discussion demonstrates that carefully triangulating rumour data may never result in the definitive, doctrinal status of any given violent event. Owing to the politicized nature of intercommunal violence in central Mali, for example, we may never know the exact number of victims in the Sobane Da massacre, since adversarial groups may have tactically exaggerated or subdued particular details in order to buttress their own position of legitimacy and their claims for support from national or foreign actors. Another important point to consider is that sometimes, in attempts to find out 'what actually happened', factual errors may be inadvertently introduced into a rumour's narrative that do not reflect empirical reality, but nevertheless adhere to commonly accepted stereotypes held by different social groups.121 Even though rumours are difficult to validate as concrete events, sliding between the factual and the imaginary, taking on subtle (or not-so-subtle) distortions as they move from subject to subject, they nevertheless express the positionality of conflict actors and provide glimpses into their world-views and concerns. Taking rumours seriously in intervention settings is crucial if interveners want to better understand how intervened-upon communities perceive and come to reinforce their 'collective lived' realities.122 Rumours, embellishments and stories, even fabricated ones, are valuable not only 'because they reflect the speaker's state of mind, aspirations, and desires', but more importantly because they shed light on the speaker's place within local fields of power.123 After all, the longevity of rumours depends less on their source than on the group within which they are shared.124 In this vein, rumours leading to conflicting accounts-for example, those held by supporters of COREN's vocal position regarding the MNLA's alleged sexual violence in Gao versus those of many Tuareg communities who nurture doubts on the matter (whether they are supporters or enemies of the MNLA)-can help to illustrate long-held intergroup prejudices and unresolved historical wounds felt by competing groups that need to be addressed. Recognizing how rumours render the trajectory of power relations visible can generate openings for new and creative thinking by interveners to address grievances that underpin more immediate, politicized events. As such, rumours can help interveners address root causes, instead of only more superficial ones. Finally, engaging directly with rumours can foster local trust and engagement since doing so necessarily involves an acknowledgement of anxieties and interests. In situations of complex asymmetric violence oscillating somewhere between peace and war, 'there is not so much an obscuring fog as there is a surfeit of information and impressions'.125 When interveners are attuned to this surfeit, they are not only able to decipher the positionality of individuals trafficking or accepting rumours, but also can better empathize with intervened-upon communities and gauge their interests and receptivity to potential collaboration. Nevertheless, doing so means acknowledging that a definitive view from which the researcher or intervener can discern violent events in their unvarnished and exact content does not exist; at least, not for the actors involved. Instead, by paying serious attention to rumours, researchers and practitioners can better attend to anxieties and insecurities, which are necessarily situational, relational and political. © 2020 Oxford University Press. All rights reserved.
