AB  - People who are bisexual are more likely than their gay and lesbian peers to report experiencing prejudice in their daily lives. Although frequently used for research, existing measures of binegativity provide an incomplete assessment of binegative attitudes, often because they were created as extensions of measures of homonegativity and racism rather than as a distinct form of prejudice. We sought to fill this void by developing a scale to measure binegativity based on (a) existing scales measuring biphobia or binegativity, (b) the scholarly literature on biphobic and binegative interactions reported by bisexual people, and (c) responses to open-ended items about bisexuality and bisexual people. Parallel item sets were created to examine potential differences in how binegativity manifests when directed toward bisexual men and women. A usable sample of 435 heterosexual participants responded to 118 potential binegativity items, and a collection of existing measures of prejudice (e.g., racism) and individual difference measures (e.g., agreeableness, socially desirable responding) for validity purposes. A multiphase item reduction procedure and exploratory factor analyses yielded three highly correlated scales to assess binegativity. Validity was supported via a host of external measures. Known-groups validity was supported across levels of political ideology and with a second sample of bisexual participants (n = 60). Our analyses resulted in the Group-Based Attitudes toward Bisexuality (GBAB), Attitudes toward Bisexual Men (ABM), and Attitudes toward Bisexual Women (ABW) scales. These scales may help us better understand binegativity, which could lead to prejudice reduction efforts that improve the lived experiences of bisexual people. © 2020 American Psychological Association.
